        {
            "id": "95529e208d5c40229d266",
            "questionText": "A nuclear power plant experiences a leak, releasing Strontium-90 ($!$Sr-90$!$) into the surrounding environment. $!$Sr-90$!$ has a half-life ($!$T_{1/2}$!$) of approximately 29 years. If the initial concentration of $!$Sr-90$!$ in the soil is measured to be $!$C_0$!$, environmental scientists determine that the safe level of concentration is $!$C_0/8$!$. How many years will it take for the concentration of $!$Sr-90$!$ in the soil to decrease to a safe level, given the random nature of radioactive decay? Use the formula $!$A = A_0 e^{-\\lambda t}$!$ to estimate the time.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "d946ff2f7103496fb4e2e",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the radioactive decay law that models the decrease in concentration of a substance over time. Which one of the following equations is the correct decay formula?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "25c877b8-9a98-41c4-9844-addf85fe40a5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$A = A_0 e^{-\\lambda t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$A = A_0 - \\lambda t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$A = A_0 (1 - \\lambda t)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "a0803f4746d449118a9c9",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider that the concentration decreases from its initial value $!$C_0$!$ to a safe level of $!$C_0/8$!$. After dividing by $!$C_0$!$, set up the equation relating the exponential term to the safe fraction. Which of the following correctly represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "25c877b8-9a98-41c4-9844-addf85fe40a5"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$e^{-\\lambda t} = 1/8$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$e^{-\\lambda t} = 8$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$e^{-\\lambda t} = 1/2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "dfd5fbcb47584521a1c22",
                    "stepText": "Next, we need to relate the decay constant $!$\\lambda$!$ to the half-life $!$T_{1/2}$!$. Which of the following formulas correctly defines $!$\\lambda$!$ in terms of the half-life?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
